# {{ hostname }} Rust + React + Postgres App

This scaffold is a production-oriented baseline for `homesrvctl app init <hostname> --template rust-react-postgres`.

It keeps the existing homesrvctl operating model:

- Cloudflare Tunnel terminates ingress for the domain
- Traefik routes the hostname to the `frontend` container
- nginx serves the built React app
- nginx proxies `/api` to the Rust backend
- Postgres stays internal to the stack on a private Compose network

## Files

- `docker-compose.yml`: frontend, API, and Postgres services
- `.env.example`: starter runtime settings for the API and database
- `.dockerignore`: keeps build cache and local env noise out of image builds
- `frontend/`: React + Vite app, nginx config, and frontend image build
- `api/`: Rust service, Dockerfile, and starter SQL migration

## First run

1. Copy `.env.example` to `.env` only if you need to override the defaults.
2. Start the stack with `docker compose up --build`.
3. Verify all three containers become healthy.
4. Confirm `https://{{ hostname }}/` serves the frontend.
5. Confirm the frontend loads data from `/api/hello`.
6. Replace the placeholder UI, API routes, and migration with your real app code.

## Runtime behavior

- Only `frontend` is exposed to Traefik.
- nginx proxies `/api` to the internal Rust service so browser requests stay one-origin.
- The Rust service exposes `GET /healthz` for internal healthchecks.
- The Rust service runs SQL migrations from `api/migrations/` on startup.
- Postgres is reachable only on the private `internal` network.

## ARM notes

The generated stack uses official multi-architecture images (`node`, `nginx`, `rust`, `debian`, and `postgres`) so it stays friendly to Raspberry Pi hosts without extra template changes.
